# CLAUDE.md — {{PROJECT}} operating manual

You are building **{{PROJECT}}**. {{PROJECT_ONE_LINER}} Read this file cold at the start of every session — you have no memory of prior sessions.

**Harness tier: SMALL.** You are the builder. There is **one** skill — `build-loop` — and you run it yourself. **Invoke `build-loop` at the start of every build session.** Where this file and `build-loop` disagree, `build-loop` wins.

There is no scoper, no separate reviewer, no gates, no epic or phase boundaries. **You scope, you build, and you review your own work.** That last part is a real weakening and you should know it — see **What this tier gave up**, below. It was accepted because at this size the orchestration overhead costs more than it returns.

## The three files that govern everything
1. `{{STATE_FILE}}` — the single source of truth for status. Read it first, always. It names the exact next story. **Write it after every single story.**
2. `{{PLAN}}` — the backlog: stories, sizes, dependencies, acceptance criteria.
3. `{{DESIGN}}` — the design contract. Its locked-decisions section holds the ADRs; its open-register section lists what is deliberately unspecified. Its **{{GLOSSARY_SECTION}} glossary** is the project's canonical vocabulary — name types, tables, and variables from it, and never from a term it lists under `Avoid`.

## What this tier gave up (read this once, honestly)

**You review your own code.** The author is judging their own work. That is exactly the conflict of interest an independent reviewer exists to remove, and no amount of discipline fully removes it: you will read your diff already believing it is correct, because you wrote it believing that. The mitigation is mechanical, not motivational — **check the acceptance criteria one at a time, against the code and the tests, and cite what satisfies each.** "I implemented the story" is not a check. "AC 3 is satisfied by `service.py:88` and `test_service.py:41`" is.

**Nothing folds deviations back into `{{DESIGN}}`.** If you deviate from the design mid-build, record it in `{{STATE_FILE}}` → `Decisions & deviations`, in one concrete line, and **never delete it**. That section is the only record. It is also *your* memory: next session you will read the design and believe it, unless that line is there to contradict it.

**Nothing catches a cross-story regression except the full suite.** Which is why you run the full suite on every story, and why a red is never negotiable.

### The upgrade trigger — this is a real instruction

If **any** of these fires, the tier was chosen wrong:

- the build passes **~15 stories**, or
- you catch yourself wanting a gate — an independent review, a composite-diff pass, a regression gate at a boundary, or
- you have deviated from the design enough times that you no longer trust it.

**Regenerate the harness at `standard`.** Do not hand-bolt a gate onto this one. A small harness silently carrying a large build is the failure mode of this tier: it keeps reporting green, story after story, while nothing is actually being checked by anyone but the person who wrote it.

