## Coding standards specific to this project

{{INVARIANTS}}

These are checkable assertions, not aspirations. Check them literally on every story. A review told "check that the code is correct" checks nothing; one told a specific invariant catches the bug.

- **Errors:** a single uniform error contract, applied everywhere; plain-language user-facing errors that state impact + next action; no stack traces or secrets to clients; never show success unless the operation completed.
{{#IF TOKENS_FILE}}- **UI components:** semantic tokens from `{{TOKENS_FILE}}` only — no raw hex/px. Status carried by icon/text, never color alone.{{/IF}}
{{#IF MIGRATION_TOOL}}- **Schema:** obey design {{SCHEMA_SECTION}} — the standard column set, CHECK-constrained states, and FK delete behavior that never loses history to a cascade.{{/IF}}

## The four rules that do not bend

Everything else at this tier is a convenience. These four are load-bearing, they cost nothing, and their absence is what kills small projects.

1. **GREEN BASELINE IS LAW.** `{{CHECK_COMMAND}}` must be fully green — **zero failing tests** — before a story is done. **Never excuse a red as "pre-existing" or "environmental" and move on.** If the fix is small and clearly right, fix it and note it. If it is not, **stop and say so** — do not build the next story on a red tree. A suite that has been red for three stories is a suite nobody is reading, and from that point on you are flying blind. The only acceptable non-green test is one legitimately skip-gated on a genuinely unavailable resource; adding a new skip to dodge a real failure is not that.
2. **One story = one commit.** Branch off `{{BRANCH}}`. Commit the story as a single commit once the suite is green, using the format below. Never batch two stories into one commit, and never leave a story's work uncommitted while starting the next — the diff stops being a story and becomes a fog.
3. **Write `{{STATE_FILE}}` after EVERY story.** Never batch. A crash, a context reset, or a closed laptop then costs you at most one story instead of a session.
4. **Check the acceptance criteria before marking a story done.** Every AC bullet, one at a time, against the code and the tests, with the `file:line` or the test that satisfies it. Not "it works." Not "I implemented it." If an AC cannot be satisfied as written, that is a blocker — record it and ask, do not quietly redefine it.

## Commits

```
{{COMMIT_FORMAT}}
<body: what changed and why, wrapped>
```

Every message ends with the `Co-Authored-By` trailer from the environment rules. Commit `{{STATE_FILE}}` along with the story — at this tier there is no separate orchestrator, so there is no reason to split it out.

## Handling ambiguity

- **Make the call** when the design under-specifies an implementation detail and there is an obvious simplest choice consistent with the surrounding design (a field name, an index, a helper's shape). **Record it** in `{{STATE_FILE}}` → `Decisions & deviations`, one line.
- **Stop and ask** when: the design contradicts itself; a decision the design's open register explicitly reserved resurfaces; an acceptance criterion cannot be met as written; or the environment cannot supply an external dependency. Record the blocker in `{{STATE_FILE}}` with a specific ask. **Never guess on a reserved decision, and never skip a blocked story to keep moving** — it blocks its dependents by design.

## When to stop

**There is no story quota and no session cap.** Keep building. Stop when, and only when:

- the backlog is complete, or
- you hit a genuine blocker, or
- a context/summarization `<system-reminder>` appears.

That is the entire list — one signal, on purpose. Every other heuristic you might reach for (the session feels long, that was a big story, this is a natural stopping point, I've done a lot) fires long before real context pressure and costs a full resume cycle for nothing.

When the context signal fires: finish or cleanly revert the in-flight story, write `{{STATE_FILE}}` with the exact next story in `NEXT ACTION`, commit, tell the user *"run `build-loop` next session to continue at `<story>`"*, and stop.

## Definition of done for the whole project

Every gate in `{{DESIGN}}` {{DOD_SECTION}} holds. The backlog is complete when every story in `{{PLAN}}` is `done`, the suite is green, and those gates pass.
